  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Yandex</strong> is the largest search engine in Russia, holding approximately 60-65% of domestic search traffic. Founded in 1997 and headquartered in Amsterdam (following its 2022 restructuring), Yandex operates its own search algorithm, paid advertising platform (Yandex Direct), maps product, and dozens of consumer services — making it the dominant technology company of the Russian-speaking internet.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Search Engines</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Russian Google</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If your business has an audience in Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, or other Russian-speaking markets, Yandex is not optional — it's the primary search engine. Understanding how it differs from Google is the starting point for international SEO in this region.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Yandex?</h2>
        <p>Yandex (stylised as Яндекс in Russian) was founded by Arkady Volozh and Ilya Segalovich in 1997, the same year as Google. The name comes from "Yet Another iNDEXer." It launched its public search product in September 1997 — three months before Google's domain was even registered.</p>
        <p>The company went public on NASDAQ in 2011 and quickly became one of the most valuable internet companies in Russia. Its product portfolio grew to include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Yandex Search</strong> — core web search, image search, video, news</li>
          <li><strong>Yandex Direct</strong> — pay-per-click advertising (equivalent to Google Ads)</li>
          <li><strong>Yandex Maps</strong> — mapping and local business listings</li>
          <li><strong>Yandex Metrica</strong> — free web analytics (equivalent to Google Analytics)</li>
          <li><strong>Yandex Webmaster</strong> — site management and indexing tools</li>
          <li><strong>Yandex Browser</strong> — Chromium-based browser with Yandex search default</li>
          <li><strong>Yandex Cloud</strong> — cloud computing and AI infrastructure</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Following Russia's invasion of Ukraine in 2022 and subsequent international sanctions, Yandex restructured significantly. Its international technology businesses were separated from its Russian consumer operations. As of 2026, the Russian search and media business operates under the Yandex brand domestically, while international AI and cloud assets were sold to a consortium.</p>

        <h2 id="market-share">Yandex's market position in 2026</h2>
        <p>Yandex holds approximately 60-65% of Russia's search market — a dominant position maintained despite heavy competition from Google (which holds roughly 35-38%). In Kazakhstan and Belarus, Yandex's share is lower but still significant, particularly for Russian-language queries.</p>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Market</th><th>Yandex share (approx.)</th><th>Google share (approx.)</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Russia</strong></td>
                <td>60-65%</td>
                <td>35-38%</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Kazakhstan</strong></td><td>30-35%</td><td>60-65%</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Belarus</strong></td><td>35-40%</td><td>55-60%</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Ukraine (pre-2022)</strong></td><td>~20%</td><td>~75%</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Yandex search ranking works</h2>
        <p>Yandex's ranking algorithm, called MatrixNet (later evolved into CatBoost-powered machine learning), differs from Google in several important ways that affect how SEOs should approach optimisation.</p>
        <h3>Behavioural signals</h3>
        <p>Yandex places heavy emphasis on behavioural metrics — particularly how users interact with search results. Click-through rate, dwell time (how long a visitor stays on your page before returning to search results), and pogo-sticking (immediately bouncing back to the SERP) are more explicitly integrated into Yandex's ranking model than Google acknowledges for its own algorithm.</p>
        <h3>On-page signals</h3>
        <p>Historically, Yandex has rewarded strong on-page keyword optimisation more aggressively than Google. Keyword density, keyword placement in H1-H3 tags, and semantic keyword variants in the body copy carry more weight on Yandex. That said, Yandex has also penalised over-optimisation — exact-match keyword stuffing triggers its Minusinsk filter (the equivalent of Google Panda for spam).</p>
        <h3>Link signals</h3>
        <p>Yandex's approach to links evolved dramatically after its 2014 announcement that it would remove commercial links (paid links for SEO purposes) as a ranking signal in Moscow — and later extended this nationally. Today, Yandex uses link signals for authority and trust assessment, but is more sceptical of artificial link patterns than older iterations of its algorithm.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Yandex's Minusinsk algorithm</div>
          <p>In 2015, Yandex introduced Minusinsk — a filter specifically targeting sites that use paid links for SEO manipulation. Sites caught in Minusinsk see their rankings drop significantly. Unlike Google's Penguin (which is algorithm-based), Minusinsk applies manual penalties, making recovery slower and more uncertain.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="yandex-vs-google">Yandex vs. Google: key differences for SEO</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Yandex</th><th>Google</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Behavioural signals</strong></td>
                <td>Very heavily weighted</td>
                <td>Weighted but not confirmed explicitly</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Link building</strong></td><td>Sceptical of commercial links</td><td>Values natural editorial links</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Keyword density</strong></td><td>More influential</td><td>Largely devalued</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Domain age</strong></td><td>Strong trust signal</td>
                <td>Less emphasised</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local results</strong></td><td>Yandex Maps + Yandex Business</td><td>Google Maps + Google Business Profile</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Analytics tool</strong></td><td>Yandex Metrica</td><td>Google Analytics / GA4</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="yandex-webmaster">Yandex Webmaster</h2>
        <p>Yandex Webmaster (webmaster.yandex.com) is the search console equivalent for Yandex. If you're targeting Russian-speaking users, setting up Yandex Webmaster is essential. Key features include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sitemap submission</strong> — submit and monitor your XML sitemap directly</li>
          <li><strong>Indexing reports</strong> — see which pages are indexed, excluded, or flagged</li>
          <li><strong>Search query data</strong> — impressions, clicks, and average position for your top queries</li>
          <li><strong>Site errors</strong> — crawl errors, broken links, and technical issues</li>
          <li><strong>Turbo pages</strong> — Yandex's version of AMP for fast-loading mobile pages</li>
          <li><strong>Site quality assessment</strong> — a score-based system that flags quality issues</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="yandex-direct">Yandex Direct (paid advertising)</h2>
        <p>Yandex Direct is Yandex's pay-per-click advertising platform. It works similarly to Google Ads — keyword-based bidding, ad groups, quality scores — but with important differences in interface, targeting options, and audience behaviour.</p>
        <p>Yandex Direct also powers the Yandex Advertising Network (YAN), a display network of partner sites where ads can appear. YAN reaches approximately 65% of the Russian internet audience, making it a valuable channel for display and retargeting campaigns targeting Russian users.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for Yandex SEO</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Register in Yandex Webmaster.</strong> Submit your sitemap and verify ownership just as you would in Google Search Console. Without this, you're flying blind on your Yandex indexing health.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritise user experience metrics.</strong> Yandex's heavy reliance on behavioural signals means pages with high bounce rates and low dwell time will struggle regardless of other SEO work. Invest in page quality and load speed.</li>
          <li><strong>Use Russian-language content written by native speakers.</strong> Machine-translated content ranks poorly on Yandex — its algorithms are well-tuned to Russian morphology and can identify unnatural language patterns.</li>
          <li><strong>Build local trust signals.</strong> Yandex places significant weight on geographic relevance. Russian-language domains (.ru), hosting in Russia, and NAP consistency on Russian business directories improve local rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Install Yandex Metrica.</strong> Yandex Metrica (analytics platform) integrates with Yandex Webmaster and provides behavioural insights. There is a credible theory that Yandex uses Metrica data from sites that have it installed to inform ranking signals — though Yandex has not confirmed this officially.</li>
          <li><strong>Avoid paid link schemes.</strong> Minusinsk penalties are severe and slow to recover from. Build links through editorial placements, partnerships, and content promotion — not link exchanges or paid placements.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Yandex SEO mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Treating Yandex the same as Google.</strong> Tactics that work on Google don't always translate. Yandex's emphasis on behavioural signals and Russian-language nuance requires a localised approach.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring Yandex Webmaster.</strong> Without the equivalent of Search Console set up, you won't know if Yandex is indexing your pages, encountering errors, or penalising your site.</li>
          <li><strong>Using auto-translated Russian content.</strong> Yandex's NLP capabilities are strong for Russian. Machine-translated content typically scores poorly on quality assessments.</li>
          <li><strong>Overlooking Yandex Maps for local businesses.</strong> For businesses with Russian locations, Yandex Maps (yandex.ru/maps) is as important as Google Maps. Claiming and optimising your Yandex Business listing is essential for local visibility.</li>
        </ul>

